## PART I: ENVIRONMENTAL & TECHNICAL FOUNDATIONS

### Section 1: Environmental Operating Constants

These environmental differences fundamentally redefine movement, timing, and gameplay structure.

| Parameter | Earth (Control) | Luna (Moon) | Mars |
|---|---|---|---|
| Gravity (g) | 9.81 m/s² | 1.62 m/s² (0.165g) | 3.71 m/s² (0.38g) |
| Max Jump Height (Standing) | ~1.5 m | ~10.0 m | ~3.9 m |
| Hang Time (Max Vert) | ~0.7 s | ~4.9 s | ~2.2 s |
| Atmosphere (Indoor Arena) | 1 atm (101 kPa) | 1 atm (Pressurized Dome) | 0.6–1.0 atm (Augmented) |

**Threshold Alert:** Research published March 13, 2026 in *Science Advances* identifies 0.67g (67% of Earth's gravity) as a critical threshold for muscle preservation. A study conducted aboard the ISS exposed mice to graded gravity levels — 0.33g, 0.67g, and 1g — and found that muscle mass, fiber type composition, and function deteriorated significantly below 0.67g. Mars, at 0.38g, falls below this threshold, while the Moon at 0.165g falls far below it. This elevates Off-World Basketball's importance as a mandatory exercise countermeasure on both worlds.

**Atmospheric Note — Mars Aerodynamic Anomaly:**
On Mars, the atmosphere is approximately 100 times less dense than Earth's. A spinning ball in rarefied air may exhibit the Reverse Magnus Effect, deflecting in the opposite direction of Earth-normal expectations. This creates non-intuitive trajectory behavior that Astroletes® must master through environment-specific training. Experimental verification of this effect in Mars pressure chambers remains a priority research objective (see Part V, Proposal 9).

